From: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] backlight: pwm: add pwm-bootloader-on for handoff scenarios

Some bootloader-handoff configurations need pwm-backlight to leave the
bootloader's running PWM and enable-GPIO state alone across kernel
probe. On Spotify Car Thing (Superbird, Amlogic G12A) u-boot brings
the ST7701S panel and its PWM-driven backlight up before kernel
handoff, and any probe-time write to those drives the panel dark for
the boot window before userspace can adjust.

Three sites in pwm_backlight_probe() write PWM/GPIO during probe:

  1. pwm_init_state() + pwm_apply_might_sleep() ("Sync up PWM state").
     pwm_init_state unconditionally sets state.duty_cycle = 0, so the
     subsequent apply on pwm-meson lands in the duty==0 branch of
     meson_pwm_calc and writes channel->hi=0 / constant=true - i.e. a
     constant-LOW output, stomping the bootloader's duty cycle. The
     enable bit itself stays set, but the panel still goes dark
     because the PWM line idles low.

  2. pwm_backlight_initial_power_state() drives the enable-gpio after
     reading the live PWM/regulator state, which on this hardware
     reads as inconsistent and resolves to BACKLIGHT_POWER_OFF.

  3. backlight_update_status() at the end of probe applies
     dft_brightness, which is too low to clear the LP8556 LED-driver
     start threshold on Superbird and shows as a visible dim.

Add a "pwm-bootloader-on" boolean DT property gating all three:

  - skip the initial pwm_apply, leave the running hardware alone
    (state is still filled in for the later lth_brightness math)
  - short-circuit pwm_backlight_initial_power_state to
    BACKLIGHT_POWER_ON, leave the enable GPIO at its bootloader value
  - skip the closing backlight_update_status - the cached
    bl->props.brightness will be applied by the first userspace
    write (sysfs, systemd-backlight, ALS service, etc.) so brightness
    controls still work, they just don't fire on probe

Default behaviour (property absent) is unchanged.

Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Upstream-Status: Pending
---
diff --git a/drivers/video/backlight/pwm_bl.c b/drivers/video/backlight/pwm_bl.c
index 237d3d3f3..5636ae8a3 100644
--- a/drivers/video/backlight/pwm_bl.c
+++ b/drivers/video/backlight/pwm_bl.c
@@ -399,6 +399,18 @@ static int pwm_backlight_initial_power_state(const struct pwm_bl_data *pb)
 	struct device_node *node = pb->dev->of_node;
 	bool active = true;

+	/*
+	 * "pwm-bootloader-on": the bootloader has the backlight up; trust
+	 * that and ignore the live PWM/enable-gpio/regulator state probes
+	 * below. Designed for handoff scenarios where some other driver
+	 * (pwm-meson, in our case) clobbers the PWM enable bit between
+	 * bootloader exit and pwm-backlight probe, which would otherwise
+	 * cause this function to pick BACKLIGHT_POWER_OFF and drive the
+	 * enable GPIO low - blanking the panel mid-handoff.
+	 */
+	if (node && of_property_read_bool(node, "pwm-bootloader-on"))
+		return BACKLIGHT_POWER_ON;
+
 	/*
 	 * If the enable GPIO is present, observable (either as input
 	 * or output) and off then the backlight is not currently active.
@@ -518,11 +530,24 @@ static int pwm_backlight_probe(struct platform_device *pdev)
 	if (!state.period && (data->pwm_period_ns > 0))
 		state.period = data->pwm_period_ns;

-	ret = pwm_apply_might_sleep(pb->pwm, &state);
-	if (ret) {
-		dev_err_probe(&pdev->dev, ret,
-			      "failed to apply initial PWM state");
-		goto err_alloc;
+	/*
+	 * "pwm-bootloader-on": skip the initial pwm_apply too.
+	 * pwm_init_state() unconditionally sets state.duty_cycle = 0, so
+	 * applying it would drive the PWM output to constant-LOW (on
+	 * pwm-meson via the meson_pwm_calc duty==0 branch), stomping the
+	 * bootloader's running duty cycle even though the enable bit
+	 * stays set. We still need state.period filled in for the
+	 * lth_brightness calculation further down - pwm_init_state has
+	 * already done that - so just gate the hardware write.
+	 */
+	if (!(pdev->dev.of_node &&
+	      of_property_read_bool(pdev->dev.of_node, "pwm-bootloader-on"))) {
+		ret = pwm_apply_might_sleep(pb->pwm, &state);
+		if (ret) {
+			dev_err_probe(&pdev->dev, ret,
+				      "failed to apply initial PWM state");
+			goto err_alloc;
+		}
 	}

 	memset(&props, 0, sizeof(struct backlight_properties));
@@ -601,7 +626,21 @@ static int pwm_backlight_probe(struct platform_device *pdev)

 	bl->props.brightness = data->dft_brightness;
 	bl->props.power = pwm_backlight_initial_power_state(pb);
-	backlight_update_status(bl);
+
+	/*
+	 * "pwm-bootloader-on": skip the initial backlight_update_status
+	 * write. Otherwise we'd immediately stomp the bootloader's PWM
+	 * duty cycle with the kernel's dft_brightness - typically much
+	 * dimmer (e.g. 5%), producing a visible flicker between the
+	 * bootloader splash and the first userspace brightness write
+	 * (systemd-backlight, ALS service, etc.). The cached
+	 * bl->props.brightness will be updated by the first
+	 * userspace-driven update_status call, so brightness controls
+	 * still work - they just won't fire on probe.
+	 */
+	if (!(pdev->dev.of_node &&
+	      of_property_read_bool(pdev->dev.of_node, "pwm-bootloader-on")))
+		backlight_update_status(bl);

 	platform_set_drvdata(pdev, bl);
 	return 0;
